<article>
    <h1>SMC must ad&#xAD;dress com&#xAD;plaints ex&#xAD;pe&#xAD;di&#xAD;tiously</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200718/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-18"><time>2020-07-18</time></a>
        - <span>SCIENCE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Heng Cho Choon</span>
    </section>

    <p>Straits Times se­nior health cor­re­spon­dent Salma Kha­lik has rightly di­ag­nosed the ail­ments af­flict­ing the Sin­ga­pore Med­i­cal Coun­cil (SMC) (Med­i­cal watch­dog body needs to move out of slow lane, July 16). As the le­gal maxim usu­ally at­trib­uted to Bri­tish politi­cian Wil­liam Ewart Glad­stone goes, jus­tice de­layed is jus­tice de­nied.</p>
    <p>Sir Don­ald Irvine, who was pres­i­dent of the Gen­eral Med­i­cal Coun­cil (GMC) in Bri­tain, once said that the self-reg­u­la­tion of the med­i­cal pro­fes­sion is a priv­i­lege, not a right.</p>
    <p>The GMC’s web­site says that it will re­ply to com­plaints within two weeks, and if an in­ves­ti­ga­tion is deemed nec­es­sary, the GMC aims to com­plete all in­ves­ti­ga­tions within 12 months.</p>
    <p>The SMC should act ex­pe­di­tiously in deal­ing with com­plaints against doc­tors, be­cause any de­lay will bring men­tal dis­tress to in­no­cent doc­tors, and pa­tients who suf­fered harm at the hands of in­com­pe­tent doc­tors will feel that jus­tice and com­pen­sa­tion are elu­sive.</p>


